Read in data

Description of data: a big CSV file that is kind of a bunch of lexical databases merged together. Includes info like frequency, concreteness, neighborhood density etc. sorted by word. Lexical databases include: English Lexicon Project, Lancaster Sensorimotor Norms, Warriner Valence Norms, Glascow Valence Norms, Kuperman Age of Acquisition norms, Subtlex Frequency Norms, and Brysbaert’s Concreteness Norms. Jamie made this and sent it to us via email.

Name the data “megalex” and clean it up. Also look at it just to make sure things worked out with the import.

Cleaning the data did result in a lot of observations being lost! We went from 73459 observations to only 3883. We have a lot of NA values in the data. Let’s use the messy dataset because I don’t want to be omitting so many observations. When I do correlation things later that means that I will need to add the ‘na.rm = TRUE’ statement when I tell R to do things.

Choose any eight variables and create a corrplot and correlation matrix

So it looks like all the the word length measures (i.e., # letters, # syllables, # phonemes) are super positively correlated, which isn’t shocking. These short words also seem to be positively correlated with age of acquisiton. It also looks like imageability and concreteness are v positively correlated too. One kind of weird thing is that familiarity and age of acquisition are fairly strongly negatively related….we would probably think more familiar words are acquired earlier. But maybe that has to do with how familiarity was measured, especially since the two measures come from different datasets.

Let’s look into the relationship between familiarity and age of acquisition. We’ll run a simple linear regression, but first will need to test assumptions of normality and homoscedasticity.

Histograms were pretty informative, but let’s do an actual test of normality. Since our sample size is so big we can’t do the shapiro-wilk test in R. We can do the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test instead because R will let us do this test with a sample size as big as ours. We will need the nortest package to do the KS test.

Remember that hetting a significant p value means the dist is NOT normal (null hypo is normal dist). So, we WANT non-significant p-values for these tests.

glimpse(MKOmegalex)  #73,459 observations!

Test homoscedasticity (homogeneity of variances assumption) with Levene Test. Null hypothesis is that variances are equal (i.e., differences between variances is zero). Nonsignificant p-values mean that variances are roughly = and assumption has not been violated.

Must activate car package first.

library(car)
levene.megalex <- leveneTest(MKOmegalex$kup_aoa, MKOmegalex$gls_fam, center = mean)
levene.megalex  #highly significant! ughhhhh. 
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = mean)
##         Df F value                Pr(>F)
## group  983  1.5504 < 0.00000000000000022
##       3428

Significant p value shows that the assumption of homogeneity of variances has been violated. We can’t assume equal variances.

According to our regression equation (which is probably not very good because we violated all assumptions) – 1) for a word with the familiarity rating of 2.4, the AoA is 13.1988 (?years/months old) 2) for a word with the familiarity rating of 3.4, the AoA is 11.4008 (?years/months old) 3) for a word with the familiarity rating of 4.4, the AoA is 9.6028 (?years/months old)
